..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:10:The NGE-era codebase (~2010 final build) is largely "pure 
NGE" â€” Pre-CU code paths are not guarded by runtime flags or `#ifdef` switches but were either 
fully removed or disabled in-place with `#if 0`. The transition artifacts that remain fall into four 
categories: (1) a single dated comment explicitly marking a Combat Upgrade deprecation; (2) ~40+ 
`#if 0` blocks across both game code and tools, with varying explanation quality; (3) three orphaned 
"Old" header stubs for a superseded resource-extraction UI; and (4) a substantial body of 
schematic-revocation infrastructure that survived the NGE because it remained needed for GM console 
commands. The largest single artifact is a 2,514-line SQL schematic conversion table in the database 
layer, which is historical record, not active code.
..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:43:**Finding:** Era-transition comments are sparse â€” the code 
was cleaned aggressively. The CommandTable comment is the only one with an explicit CU/NGE 
attribution and author/date.
..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:72:The MayaExporter, TerrainEditor, AnimationDialog, and Viewer 
applications account for the majority of `#if 0` instances in `src/engine/`. These are 
artist-tool-specific disabled experimental features and are unrelated to the Pre-CUâ†’NGE transition.
..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:80:**Runtime guards:** No `if (useOldSystem)`, `if 
(preCuBehavior)`, or similar boolean guards on era-branching code paths were found in `src/engine/` 
or `src/game/`. The NGE codebase does not use runtime feature flags to select between Pre-CU and NGE 
behaviors â€” it is a clean cut.
..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:82:**`#ifdef` guards:** No `#ifdef OLD_*`, `#ifdef LEGACY_*`, 
`#ifdef PRE_CU`, or `#ifdef NGE` macros found in C++ source.
..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:86:**Finding:** The transition was implemented as a hard code 
replacement, not feature-flagged branching. There are no active runtime branches selecting Pre-CU vs 
NGE behavior.
..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:102:The `Old` suffix names a pre-NGE resource extraction UI that 
was replaced. The source implementations were deleted; the public forwarding headers were left 
behind, pointing at nothing. Including these headers would immediately produce a compiler error 
("file not found"). They are safe to delete.
..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:141:These files in `src/game/server/database/item_conversion/` 
document the live-to-NGE player inventory conversion that ran at NGE launch. They are not active C++ 
code paths â€” they are data files consumed by a one-time migration script:
..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:145:| `armor_conversion.txt` | 242 | Tab-delimited: Pre-CU armor 
template â†’ NGE armor template + new script assignments |
..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:153:| `schematics_map.sql` | **2,514** | SQL: complete schematic 
template remapping for the NGE conversion |
..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:158:The `schematics_map.sql` at 2,514 lines is the single 
largest era-transition artifact in the repository. It maps every Pre-CU/CU schematic template path 
to its NGE equivalent (or marks it as deprecated/removed).
..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:164:**Finding:** No broken asset references in C++. The item 
conversion directory is a complete historical record of the NGE transition migration â€” 8 
conversion tables, a generation script, a 2,514-line schematic SQL map, and 5 hotfix patches.
..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:179:| Schematic revocation infrastructure | Maintained code â€” 
still needed for GM commands; CU-era origin but active in NGE |
..\docs\recon\pre-cu-archaeology.md:188:*Survey method: targeted `grep` sweeps across `src/engine/` 
and `src/game/` for CU/NGE keywords, `#if 0` patterns, and `Old`/`Legacy`/`Deprecated` naming; 
direct file reads to verify agent-reported findings; line-count checks on conversion tables.*
